SOUP: A new approach in handling Imbalanced Multi-class problems¶

Highlights¶

  • Safety coefficients can be efficiently exploited in resampling techniques to improve classifiers.
  • SOUP looks at the complex relations between classes and proposed a dataset with reasonable size.
  • SOUP works significantly better than SMOTE if samples from different classes are overlapping.

Background¶

Up to now many specialized methods for improving the classification of imbalanced data have been introduced. However, most of the current research concerns binary classification problems. Moreover, multiclass imbalanced classification problems are more difficult than their binary counterparts. The most well-known resampling technique for imbalanced multi-class problems is SMOTE, which stands for Synthetic Minority Over-sampling TEchnique. SMOTE is an oversampling approach that creates synthetic minority class samples.

However, class imbalances are often accompanied by data difficulty factors. Factors include the overlapping between the classes or the presence of many minority class examples inside the majority class region. As a result, examples from these overlapped regions, which belong to different classes and have similar attribute descriptions, usually negatively influence predictive accuracy. The need for richer modeling complex relations between classes, which is missed by current approaches led the proposal of SOUP.

Lango et al.(2017) proposed a hybrid resampling technique SOUP which stands for Similarity Oversampling and Undersampling Preprocessing. The concept behind this proposed technique is first removing the most harmful majority class examples and then oversampling the most important minority ones according to their safe levels which had resulted from analyzing their neighborhood.

Figure 1. Safe and Unsafe examples

To understand the algorithm behind SOUP, we start with defining safe and unsafe examples.Safe examplesare the ones located in homogeneous regions populated by examples from one class only.Unsafe examplesare categorized into borderline, rare cases and outliers, and more difficult for learning. To measure safe level of a sample we use equation 1.

\begin{equation} safe(x_{C_i})= \frac 1 n\sum{n_{C_j} \mu_{ij}} \tag{1} \end{equation}

where $n_{_}$ refers to the number of examples from class $_$ inside the considered neighborhood of x, $n$ is the total number of neighbors, $|_ |$ is the number of samples belonging to class i and $\mu_{ij}$ refers to degree of similarity and can be computed using equation 2. \begin{equation} \mu_{ij} = \frac {\min(|C_i|, |C_j|)} {\max(|C_i|, |C_j|)} \tag{2} \end{equation}

Figure 2. General Process in SOUP algorithm

After measuring the safe levels of the samples per each class, th undersampling of the majority classes is performed by removing the most unsafe examples until a desired class cardinality is obtained. In this way, the undersampling process is focused on the examples lying closely to minority examples or inside their regions. The oversampling of minority classes is performed by dplicating the safest examples first, enhancing the representation of clear minority concepts. The final size of the resampled dataset has $m$ samples for each class. Size $m$ is computed using equation 3. SOUP provides not only a dataset with a balanced class distribution, but also with a reasonable size.

\begin{equation} m = mean \big(\max(N_{i_{MIN}}), \min(M_{i_{MAJ}}) \big) \tag{3} \end{equation}

where $m$ is the final size of the all classes, $N_{i_{MIN}}$ refers to the sizes of all minority classes, and $M_{i_{MAJ}}$ refers to the sizes of all the majority class.

The SOUP parameters were the following:

param k:
    number of neighbors, default is 7.
param shuffle:
    bool - output will be shuffled
param maj_int_min:
    dict {'maj': majority class labels, 'min': minority class labels}

    df_tmp = pd.DataFrame(arr)

ML Implementation: The Glass Multi-class Problem¶

To evaluate the performance of the SOUP resampling method, the traditional SMOTE resampling will be implemented as well. The dataset that will be used in this project is from UCI. The Glass Dataset contains 214 rows with 11 attributes. The objective for this problem is to predict the type of glass based on the refractive index and the concentrations of different elements in the glass. The link of the dataset is found here.

Methodology¶

Figure 3. Step by step process for the Glass Multi-Class Problem

Data Description¶

Attributes¶

  1. Id number: 1 to 214
  2. RI: refractive index
  3. Na: Sodium (unit measurement: weight percent in corresponding oxide, as are attributes 4-10)
  4. Mg: Magnesium
  5. Al: Aluminum
  6. Si: Silicon
  7. K: Potassium
  8. Ca: Calcium
  9. Ba: Barium
  10. Fe: Iron
  11. Type of glass: (class attribute)
    • 1 : building_windows_float_processed
    • 2 : building_windows_non_float_processed
    • 3 : vehicle_windows_float_processed
    • 4 : vehicle_windows_non_float_processed (none in this database)
    • 5 : containers
    • 6 : tableware
    • 7 : headlamps

Results and Discussion¶

This section shows the implementation of SOUP on the imbalance dataset. There are 8 machine learning classification models used in this problem. To evaluate the performance of SOUP, we compare the G-mean score of the models using the original dataset and when the dataset is resampled using SOUP and SMOTE.

In order to prepare data for training, we will split the data for train and test subsets and normalize it. For both operations, we will use tools available in sklearn.

Training¶

The training will be performed using different ML classifiers from sklearn library. For simplicity, the default parameters are used for all classifiers.

To evaluate predictions to multi-imbalanced class we apply generalized G-mean of sensitives of each class: $$ gmean = (\Pi_{i=1}^n sensitivity_i)^{\frac{1}{n}}$$

# budget automl

res_orig = {}

# log start time
total_start = time.time()

for model_name, model in tqdm(models_dict.items()):

    start_time = time.time() # for logging run times
    kfold = KFold(n_splits=3, random_state=seed, shuffle=True)
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(estimator=model, X=X_train, y=y_train,
                                scoring=scorer, cv=kfold, n_jobs=-1)
    average_cv_score = np.mean(cv_scores)
    #retrain again
    model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    gmean = gmean_score(y_test, y_pred, correction=0.001)
        
    end_time = time.time() # for logging run times

    res_orig[model_name] = {
        'ave_train_g_mean': average_cv_score*100,
        'ave_val_g_mean': gmean* 100,
        'run_time': end_time - start_time
    }

# log end time
total_end = time.time()
elapsed = total_end - total_start
print(f"Report Generated in {elapsed:.2f} seconds")
res_orig = pd.DataFrame(res_orig).T
display(res_orig)

In [34]:



    


def get_most_important_feature(idx, name, feature, model):
    coefs = model.coef_[idx] 
    coefs_count = len(coefs)
    abs_coefs = np.abs(coefs)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6,5))
    ax.barh(np.arange(coefs_count), sorted(abs_coefs))

    ax.set_yticks(np.arange(coefs_count))
    ax.set_yticklabels(feature[np.argsort(abs_coefs)])
    most_imp = np.abs(coefs).argmax()
    print('For', name, 'the Top predictor is',feature[most_imp]+
          ' using the model '+ str(model)+'.')

The dataset is split into 70/30 for training and test set, respectively. 3-Fold cross-validation is used in the training the models. The classifiers used are KNN, Logistic Regressor, Linear SVM, RBF SVM, Gaussian Naive Bayes, Random Forest, Decision Trees, and Gradient Boosting classifiers.


Originally, the training data is composed of 49 and 53 samples for type 1 and 2 glasses. There are only 12, 9, 6, 20 samples for type 3, 5, 6, 7 glasses. After resampling with SOUP, all classes have 34 samples. However, resampling the original training set with SMOTE still gives a balance dataset with 53 samples for each class.


Using only the default parameters for our 8 models, our best model for this problem is the Logistic Regression. When the model is trained on the SOUP resampled dataset, the G-mean score is 79.2%. Training this model using SMOTE resampled dataset gives a G-mean score of 70.2%. Resampling the original data signficantly improves Logistic regression model. G-mean score is only 21.1% if the model is trained on the original data.


Linear SVM trained from the resampled SOUP dataset is the second best performing model with a G-mean score of 70.7%. If we trained a default Linear SVM with dataset resampled from SMOTE, the G-mean score is around 65.5%. However, GaussianNB and DecisionTree classifiers did not improve when they are trained from the dataset resampled with SOUP.


Looking at the best model that is trained from the resampled data using SOUP, Logistic Regressor, the most important feature for each class is different. For type 1 glass, the most important predictor is the Refractive index. For type 2 glass, the most important is the Calcium concentration of the glass. The refractive index is also the most important feature for Type 3 glass. For types 5 and 6, the most important features are Sodium concentration while Magnesium concentration for type 7 glass.















Conclusion¶














SOUP is a hybrid resampling technique that considers the mutual relations between classes. It uses safety coefficients that can be efficiently exploited in resampling techniques to improve classifiers. In the Glass Prediction Problem, the original samples have overlapping features when projected. There is also an imbalance between classes. This project shows that SOUP is an effective resampling technique for this case since overlapping samples which can be rare, borderlines or outliers will be removed before resampling. This enhances the representation of each class.


However, it is recommended to apply the SOUP technique to other multi-class imbalance data and compare it with other resampling methods. In this project, SOUP is only compared to SMOTE.
